05315nam a22007815i 9781845459772DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20102010nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97818454597727 a10.1515/97818454597722doi  a(DE-B1597)637176  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aP90b.C66 2013 7aHIS0370602bisacsh04a302.23422300aConstructing Charisma :bCelebrity, Fame, and Power in Nineteenth-Century Europe /ced. by Edward Berenson, Eva Giloi. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (244 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Illustrations -- tIntroduction -- tPart I: Constructing Charisma -- t1. Charisma and the Making of Imperial Heroes in Britain and France, 1880–1914 -- t2. “So Writes the Hand that Swings the Sword” -- t3. The Workings of Royal Celebrity -- tPart II: Celebrity as Performance -- t4. From the Top -- t5. Celebrity Gifting -- t6. Rethinking Female Celebrity -- tPart III: The Politics of Fame -- t7. Byron, Death, and the Afterlife -- t8. The Historical Actor -- t9. Celebrity, Patriotism, and Sarah Bernhardt -- t10 Heroes, Celebrity, and the Theater in Fin-de-Siècle France -- tConclusion: Secular Anointings -- tNotes -- tNotes on Contributors -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRailroads, telegraphs, lithographs, photographs, and mass periodicals—the major technological advances of the 19th century seemed to diminish the space separating people from one another, creating new and apparently closer, albeit highly mediated, social relationships. Nowhere was this phenomenon more evident than in the relationship between celebrity and fan, leader and follower, the famous and the unknown. By mid-century, heroes and celebrities constituted a new and powerful social force, as innovations in print and visual media made it possible for ordinary people to identify with the famous; to feel they knew the hero, leader, or "star"; to imagine that public figures belonged to their private lives. This volume examines the origins and nature of modern mass media and the culture of celebrity and fame they helped to create. Crossing disciplines and national boundaries, the book focuses on arts celebrities (Sarah Bernhardt, Byron and Liszt); charismatic political figures (Napoleon and Wilhelm II); famous explorers (Stanley and Brazza); and celebrated fictional characters (Cyrano de Bergerac).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aMass mediaxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 19th Century.2bisacsh1 aApter, Emily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerenson, Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerenson, Edward, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBraudy, Leo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDatta, Venita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFritzsche, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiloi, Eva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiloi, Eva, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGooley, Dana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKohlrausch, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMinta, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoberts, Mary Louise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSilver, Kenneth E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gru